WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:09.840
G'day, my name is David Shaw and I'm the Secretary of Aerospace Education Competitions,

00:09.840 --> 00:14.640
the non-profit that runs the International Space Settlement Design Competition.

00:14.640 --> 00:19.360
I'm one of the many volunteers around the globe that makes this event happen.

00:19.360 --> 00:23.240
I often get asked why I choose to invest my time here.

00:23.240 --> 00:28.360
The answer is simple, design competitions are unique and they work.

00:28.360 --> 00:33.560
There is nothing else like them in the education sphere.

00:33.560 --> 00:39.040
We provide high school students the opportunity to learn what it's like to work in the space

00:39.040 --> 00:46.080
sector and give them the chance to practice hands-on STEM well before university, let

00:46.080 --> 00:47.080
alone the workplace.

00:47.080 --> 00:52.880
And if you want an example of the success of our events, look no further.

00:52.880 --> 00:53.960
That's right.

00:53.960 --> 01:00.000
Back in 2003, I was one of the team members that was invited to the Kennedy Space Centre

01:00.000 --> 01:04.360
as the first ever finalist team from the Southern Hemisphere.

01:04.360 --> 01:08.320
And at the time, I can remember I was at high school, I wasn't sure if I wanted to study

01:08.320 --> 01:12.760
law or engineering when I went to university.

01:12.760 --> 01:18.840
During the ISSDC finals, not only was I mentored by an engineer who had worked on Apollo, but

01:18.840 --> 01:24.400
I spent a whole weekend being around other students just like me.

01:24.400 --> 01:29.920
And from that moment on, law was out, engineering was in, and I'm now where I am today in no

01:29.920 --> 01:35.440
small part due to my experience at the ISSDC finals.

01:35.440 --> 01:38.360
So why do I volunteer?

01:38.360 --> 01:43.960
Because this event changed my life and if I can give back and help just one student

01:43.960 --> 01:46.280
change their life, then it's worth it.

